{"title_page": "Peter Draffin", "text_new": "'''Peter Francey Draffin''' (25 March 1947 \u2013 22 November 2019)<ref name=\"death2016\">{{Cite web|url=https://tributes.smh.com.au/obituaries/108434/peter-francey-draffin/|title=Peter Francey Draffin|last=|first=|date=30 November 2019|website=Sydney Morning Herald Tributes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>Draffin, birth. 25 March 1947 (Family Notices, Fri 28 March 1947, P. 16). [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/title/35 ''Sydney Morning Herald Archives''] 1843-1954. Trove, National Library of Australia.</ref> was an Australian author prolific in the 1960s and 1970s. \n{{Infobox Author\n| name = Peter Draffin\n| birth_date = 25 March 1947\n| death_date = 22 November 2019\n| nationality = Australian\n| death_place = Sydney, New South Wales, Australia\n| pseudonym = Peter Draffin, [sometimes] Julian Spenser\n| native_name_lang = English\n| birth_name = Peter Francey Draffin\n| language = Australian English\n| notable_works = Pop\n| spouse = Dianne Leslie Irwin (m. 1969, deceased 1986)\n| children = Christabel Draffin\n| birth_place = New South Wales, Australia\n| movement = Counterculture\n| education = [[Tudor House School]], [[Cranbrook School, Sydney]], [[University of Sydney]]\n}}\n== Early years ==\nHis education began at [[Tudor House School|Tudor House]] School in [[Moss Vale, New South Wales|Moss Vale]], New South Wales, and continued at [[List of Cranbrook School, Sydney alumni|Cranbrook School]], Sydney,  both of which list him as a notable alumnus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cranbrook.nsw.edu.au/community/the-old-cranbrookians-association.aspx|title=Old Cranbrookians website|last=|first=|date=|website=www.cranbrook.nsw.edu.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Representing Cranbrook he achieved a 1st in the 1964 [[Australian Rowing Championships]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1964|title=1964 National Championships, Australian Rowing History|website=www.rowinghistory-aus.info|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Described by rock climber [[John Ewbank (climber)|John Ewbank]] as a \"very eccentric young man\" Draffin was also secretary of the Sydney Rock Climbing Club while at Cranbrook.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verticallifemag.com.au/2014/03/john-ewbank-ironmongers-of-the-dreamtime/|title=John Ewbank - Ironmongers of the Dreamtime|date=2014-03-03|website=Vertical Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nHe studied literature at the [[University of Sydney]] but, drawn more towards creative than academic pursuits, chose not to complete his degree.<ref name=\"abraxus2016\">{{Cite book|last=Tarling|first=Lowell|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/sharp-road-to-abraxas-part-one-1942-1979-the-biography-of-martin-sharp-as-told-to-lowell-tarling/oclc/964201806|title=Sharp: road to Abraxas. Part one: 1942-1979 : the biography of Martin Sharp as told to Lowell Tarling|date=2016|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-925416-58-9|location=|pages=|language=English|oclc=964201806}}</ref>\n\nHe married Dianne Leslie Irwin in Moss Vale in 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familyhistory.bdm.nsw.gov.au/|title=NSW Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages|last=Peter Draffin|first=Dianne Leslie Irwin|date=1969|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"gittoes2016\">{{Cite book|last=Gittoes|first=George|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/blood-mystic/oclc/959961928|title=Blood mystic|last2=Adams|first2=Phillip|date=2016|isbn=978-1-74353-480-9|language=English|oclc=959961928}}</ref> His wife died on 7 February 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ryersonindex.org/index.htm|title=The Ryerson Index|last=Draffin|first=Dianne Leslie. Death notice, 07 Feb 1986, late of Artarmon. (Notice printed 11 Feb 1986, Sydney Morning Herald.)|date=|website=ryersonindex.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>Draffin, Dianne Leslie. Death notice, 07 Feb 1986, late of Artarmon. (Notice printed 11 Feb 1986.) [https://nla.gov.au/nla.cat-vn4087953 ''Sydney Morning Herald Archives'']1955-1995. National Library of Australia</ref> Their only child is Christabel Draffin.<ref name=\"sharp2\">{{Cite book|last=Tarling|first=Lowell|url=https://public.ebookcentral.proquest.com/choice/publicfullrecord.aspx?p=5643071|title=Sharper 1980-2013: a Biography of Martin Sharp.|date=2017|publisher=ETT Imprint|isbn=978-1-925706-17-8|location=La Vergne|language=English|oclc=1084335022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://christabeldraffin.com/projects|title=Christabel Draffin {{!}} London Makeup Artist {{!}} Fashion, Beauty, Red Carpet|website=christabeldraffin.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Peak years ==\nDraffin mostly wrote as Peter Draffin but sometimes under the ''[[nom de plume]]'' Julian Spenser.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/OLD?id=A-87&idtype=oldid|title=Julian Spenser: (author/organisation) {{!}} AustLit: Discover Australian Stories|website=www.austlit.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nHis most notable novel was the [[psychedelia]]-inspired ''Pop'' (1967), illustrated throughout by [[Yellow House Artist Collective]] founder [[Martin Sharp]] (also a [[List of Cranbrook School, Sydney alumni|Cranbrook alumnus]]) and published by Scripts Pty Ltd.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Draffin|first=Peter|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/pop/oclc/220697118|title=Pop|date=1967|publisher=Scripts|location=Sydney|language=English|oclc=220697118}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Draffin|first=Peter|url=https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/2388977|title=Pop|last2=Sharp|first2=Martin|date=1967|publisher=Scripts|edition= 1st|location=London ; Melbourne|oclc=215614064}}</ref> ''Pop'' became a beat book collector's item with the passage of time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatbooks.com/pages/books/37492/peter-draffin/pop-a-novelty?soldItem=true|title=Pop - A Novelty by Peter Draffin on BeatBooks|last=www.bibliopolis.com|first=|date=|website=BeatBooks|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.antiquesreporter.com.au/index.cfm/lot/920929-peter-draffin-with-illustrated-by-martin-sharp-1942-2013-pop-a-n/|title=Peter Draffin, with Illustrated\u2026 - Estate of Jennifer Phipps - Mossgreen Auctions - Antiques Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=www.antiquesreporter.com.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abebooks.com/Pop-Novelty-Martin-Sharp-Draffin-Peter/30145627943/bd|title=Pop A Novelty by Peter Draffin, (Martin Sharp, illus.): (1967) {{!}} lamdha books|last=|first=|date=|website=www.abebooks.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nDraffin and Sharp formed a lasting association through their collaboration for ''Pop''. Draffin receives mention accordingly throughout Sharp's biographies by Lowell Tarling, to which he contributed commentary and interviews.<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" /><ref name=\"sharp2\" />\n\nWith Draffin still in Sydney, Sharp recalled illustrating ''Pop'' partly while \"tramping the [[hippie trail]] through Asia\" with [[Oz (magazine)|''Oz'']] magazine's [[Richard Neville (writer)|Richard Neville]].<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" />\n\nOnce ''Pop'' was in the printers, Draffin left Sydney to join [[Expatriate|expat]] Australian arts comrades in [[Swinging Sixties|Swinging London]], stopping en route on the Balearic island of [[Formentera|Formentara]].\n\nSharp, by then already London based but craving sunshine, joined Draffin as his houseguest on Formentara and began writing the poem that lyricised [[Tales of Brave Ulysses]], which Sharp later co-wrote for British rock band [[Cream (band)|Cream]].<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" />\n\nThe pair's houseguest roles were reversed for London. In an interview Draffin recalled being Sharpe's guest at [[The Pheasantry]] at 152 King's Road, Chelsea, before being moved out to accommodate [[Eric Clapton]].<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" />\n\nOthers living at The Pheasantry at around this time included [[David Litvinoff]] who worked in artist [[Timothy Whidborne|Tim Whidborne's]] studio there, writer [[Anthony Haden-Guest]], photographer [[Robert Whitaker (photographer)|Robert Whitaker]], and [[Germaine Greer]] who was writing ''[[The Female Eunuch]]'' in a room there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milesago.com/misc/sharp.htm|title=Martin Sharp|last=Weight|first=Greg|date=|website=MILESAGO|publisher=First published in Australian Artist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>Bell, Lynne (31 July 1969). \"Doctor who refuses to be type-cast\". ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. p. 19.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kleinhenz|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/germaine-the-life-of-germaine-greer/oclc/1046086370|title=Germaine: the life of Germaine Greer|date=2018|isbn=978-0-14-378284-1|language=English|oclc=1046086370}}</ref>\n\nLife at The Pheasantry placed Draffin and other residents at the epicentre of London's counter-cultural life.<ref>{{Cite book|last=D\u00e9charn\u00e9|first=Max|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/kings-road-the-rise-and-fall-of-the-hippest-street-in-the-world/oclc/954762096|title=King's Road: the rise and fall of the hippest street in the world|date=2005|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|isbn=978-0-297-84769-4|location=London|language=English|oclc=954762096}}</ref>\n\nAs an arts [[Counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] figure, Draffin was recognised as much as a face of the times as an author.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mellor|first=David|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/sixties-britain-and-france-1962-1973-the-utopian-years/oclc/56068696|title=The sixties: Britain and France, 1962-1973 : the utopian years|last2=Gervereau|first2=Laurent|date=1997|publisher=Philip Wilson ; Distributed in the USA and Canada by Antique Collectors' Club|year=|isbn=978-0-85667-467-9|location=London; Wappingers' Falls, NY|pages=(P. 25 Draffin photo)|oclc=56068696}}</ref> In that context he is mentioned in Yellow House co-founder [[George Gittoes]]' autobiography ''Blood Mystic'' (2016) and two Martin Sharp biographies.<ref name=\"gittoes2016\" /><ref name=\"abraxus2016\" /><ref name=\"sharp2\" />\n\nIn the late 1960s and early 1970s Draffin was a regular fiction contributor to [[K.G. Murray Publishing Company]]'s ''Man'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4535.htm|title=The FictionMags Index|last=|first=|date=|website=www.philsp.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philsp.com/data/data313.html#MAN|title=Man: Australian Magazine for Men|last=|first=|date=|website=www.philsp.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\"man2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/s/s2640.htm#A57340|title=Stories, Listed by Author|last=|first=|date=|website=www.philsp.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> He wrote feature articles for the [[Alternative culture|alternative]]/[[Underground press|underground]] magazine [[Oz (magazine)|''Oz'']] and lifestyle articles for [[Penthouse (magazine)|''Penthouse'']] magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1025&context=ozsydney|title=Oz Issue 26, March 1966|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Wollongong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"man2016\" /> He reviewed books for [[Phillip Frazer]]'s counterculture magazine ''Revolution.''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frazer|first=Phillip|date=1971-03-01|title=Revolution 2(2) March 1971|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/revolution/7|journal=Revolution|volume=|pages=|via=University of Wollongong}}</ref>\n\nThough some commentators have categorised Draffin as a [[Pulp magazine|pulp fiction]] writer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clintonwalker.com.au/lowest-of-the-low-8.html|title=Pulp Fiction|last=|first=|date=|website=Lowest of the Low, Clinton Walker|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://australianpulpfiction.blogspot.com/2008/08/who-are-these-people_21.html|title=Who are these people?|last=Ra|first=Jo|date=2008-08-21|website=A World of Australian Pulp Fiction|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> his body of work is eclectic and includes poetry, such as his 1968 ''A Dream of You''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C218211|title=A Dream of You {{!}} AustLit: Discover Australian Stories|last=Draffin|first=Peter: Australian Letters (periodical issue) vol. 8 no. 1, January 1968, pg. 67|date=|website=www.austlit.edu.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\nAs an Australian post-[[Beat Generation]] figure, Draffin became a favoured consultant and interviewee in later life, receiving credit from novelists and biographers researching the [[History of the hippie movement|hippie]] and counterculture scene.<ref name=\"sharp2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Lowell Tarling|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/1967-this-is-it/oclc/1142800905|title=1967 - This Is It|date=2020|publisher=ETT Imprint|year=|isbn=978-1-922384-13-3|location=S.l.|pages=|language=English|oclc=1142800905}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Burrough|first=C. S|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/or-forever-be-damned/oclc/896890074|title=Or forever be damned|date=2014|isbn=978-1-5008-6725-6|language=English|oclc=896890074}}</ref>\n\nDraffin was photographed with other notable Australians by Jon Lewis, for the [[Australian Bicentenary|Australian Bicentennial]] exhibition ''Face to Face \u2013 200 portraits 1986-1988'' which was purchased in 2001 by the [[National Museum of Australia]].<ref name=\"pete2008\">{{Cite web|url=http://collectionsearch.nma.gov.au/object/184760|title=Peter Draffin Portrait|last=|first=|date=|website=National Museum of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDraffin became teetotal for the last eighteen years of his life and still wrote daily, using manual typewriters, having always eschewed technology.<ref name=\"sharp2\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nHis ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]]'' tribute attracted Australian arts figures, including some from Draffin's halcyon days, to his [[Chippendale, New South Wales|Chippendale]] memorial service on 2 December 2019.<ref name=\"death2016\" />\n\nHis books remain in Australia's State and National Libraries, while his portrait remains with the National Museum of Australia.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Draffin|first=Peter|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/21842940|title=Pop|last2=Sharp|first2=Martin|date=1967|publisher=London ; Melbourne : Scripts|edition= 1st|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"pete2008\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.sl.nsw.gov.au/permalink/f/1ocrdrt/SLNSW_ALMA2196030090002626|title=Pop|last=Draffin|first=Peter|date=|website=State Library of New South Wales|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.slv.vic.gov.au/permalink/f/1cl35st/SLV_VOYAGER77093|title=Pop|last=Draffin|first=Peter|date=|website=State Library of Victoria|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://onesearch.slq.qld.gov.au/permalink/f/1oppkg1/slq_alma21128041070002061|title=Pop|last=Draffin|first=Peter|date=|website=State Library of Queensland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://collectionsearch.nma.gov.au/object/184760 National Museum of Australia portrait of Peter Draffin]\n* [https://tributes.smh.com.au/obituaries/108434/peter-francey-draffin/ ''Sydney Morning Herald'' obituary of Peter Draffin]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian writers]]\n[[Category:Australian novelists]]\n[[Category:Australian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Australian male writers]]\n[[Category:Australian male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Peter Francey Draffin''' (25 March 1947 \u2013 22 November 2019)<ref name=\"death2016\">{{Cite web|url=https://tributes.smh.com.au/obituaries/108434/peter-francey-draffin/|title=Peter Francey Draffin|last=|first=|date=30 November 2019|website=Sydney Morning Herald Tributes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>Draffin, birth. 25 March 1947 (Family Notices, Fri 28 March 1947, P. 16). [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/title/35 ''Sydney Morning Herald Archives''] 1843-1954. Trove, National Library of Australia.</ref> was an Australian author prolific in the 1960s and 1970s. \n\n{{Infobox Author\n| name = Peter Draffin\n| birth_date = 25 March 1947\n| death_date = 22 November 2019\n| nationality = Australian\n| death_place = Sydney, New South Wales, Australia\n| pseudonym = Peter Draffin, [sometimes] Julian Spenser\n| native_name_lang = English\n| birth_name = Peter Francey Draffin\n| language = Australian English\n| notable_works = Pop\n| spouse = Dianne Leslie Irwin (m. 1969, deceased 1986)\n| children = Christabel Draffin\n| birth_place = New South Wales, Australia\n| movement = Counterculture\n| education = [[Tudor House School]], [[Cranbrook School, Sydney]], [[University of Sydney]]\n}}\n== Early years ==\nHis education began at [[Tudor House School|Tudor House]] School in [[Moss Vale, New South Wales|Moss Vale]], New South Wales, and continued at [[List of Cranbrook School, Sydney alumni|Cranbrook School]], Sydney,  both of which list him as a notable alumnus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cranbrook.nsw.edu.au/community/the-old-cranbrookians-association.aspx|title=Old Cranbrookians website|last=|first=|date=|website=www.cranbrook.nsw.edu.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Representing Cranbrook he achieved a 1st in the 1964 [[Australian Rowing Championships]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1964|title=1964 National Championships, Australian Rowing History|website=www.rowinghistory-aus.info|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Described by rock climber [[John Ewbank (climber)|John Ewbank]] as a \"very eccentric young man\" Draffin was also secretary of the Sydney Rock Climbing Club while at Cranbrook.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verticallifemag.com.au/2014/03/john-ewbank-ironmongers-of-the-dreamtime/|title=John Ewbank - Ironmongers of the Dreamtime|date=2014-03-03|website=Vertical Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nHe studied literature at the [[University of Sydney]] but, drawn more towards creative than academic pursuits, chose not to complete his degree.<ref name=\"abraxus2016\">{{Cite book|last=Tarling|first=Lowell|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/sharp-road-to-abraxas-part-one-1942-1979-the-biography-of-martin-sharp-as-told-to-lowell-tarling/oclc/964201806|title=Sharp: road to Abraxas. Part one: 1942-1979 : the biography of Martin Sharp as told to Lowell Tarling|date=2016|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-925416-58-9|location=|pages=|language=English|oclc=964201806}}</ref>\n\nHe married Dianne Leslie Irwin in Moss Vale in 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familyhistory.bdm.nsw.gov.au/|title=NSW Registry of Births, Deaths and Marriages|last=Peter Draffin|first=Dianne Leslie Irwin|date=1969|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"gittoes2016\">{{Cite book|last=Gittoes|first=George|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/blood-mystic/oclc/959961928|title=Blood mystic|last2=Adams|first2=Phillip|date=2016|isbn=978-1-74353-480-9|language=English|oclc=959961928}}</ref> His wife died on 7 February 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ryersonindex.org/index.htm|title=The Ryerson Index|last=Draffin|first=Dianne Leslie. Death notice, 07 Feb 1986, late of Artarmon. (Notice printed 11 Feb 1986, Sydney Morning Herald.)|date=|website=ryersonindex.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>Draffin, Dianne Leslie. Death notice, 07 Feb 1986, late of Artarmon. (Notice printed 11 Feb 1986.) [https://nla.gov.au/nla.cat-vn4087953 ''Sydney Morning Herald Archives'']1955-1995. National Library of Australia</ref> Their only child is Christabel Draffin.<ref name=\"sharp2\">{{Cite book|last=Tarling|first=Lowell|url=https://public.ebookcentral.proquest.com/choice/publicfullrecord.aspx?p=5643071|title=Sharper 1980-2013: a Biography of Martin Sharp.|date=2017|publisher=ETT Imprint|isbn=978-1-925706-17-8|location=La Vergne|language=English|oclc=1084335022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://christabeldraffin.com/projects|title=Christabel Draffin {{!}} London Makeup Artist {{!}} Fashion, Beauty, Red Carpet|website=christabeldraffin.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Peak years ==\nDraffin mostly wrote as Peter Draffin but sometimes under the ''[[nom de plume]]'' Julian Spenser.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/OLD?id=A-87&idtype=oldid|title=Julian Spenser: (author/organisation) {{!}} AustLit: Discover Australian Stories|website=www.austlit.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nHis most notable novel was the [[psychedelia]]-inspired ''Pop'' (1967), illustrated throughout by [[Yellow House Artist Collective]] founder [[Martin Sharp]] (also a [[List of Cranbrook School, Sydney alumni|Cranbrook alumnus]]) and published by Scripts Pty Ltd.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Draffin|first=Peter|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/pop/oclc/220697118|title=Pop|date=1967|publisher=Scripts|location=Sydney|language=English|oclc=220697118}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Draffin|first=Peter|url=https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/2388977|title=Pop|last2=Sharp|first2=Martin|date=1967|publisher=Scripts|edition= 1st|location=London ; Melbourne|oclc=215614064}}</ref> ''Pop'' became a beat book collector's item with the passage of time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatbooks.com/pages/books/37492/peter-draffin/pop-a-novelty?soldItem=true|title=Pop - A Novelty by Peter Draffin on BeatBooks|last=www.bibliopolis.com|first=|date=|website=BeatBooks|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.antiquesreporter.com.au/index.cfm/lot/920929-peter-draffin-with-illustrated-by-martin-sharp-1942-2013-pop-a-n/|title=Peter Draffin, with Illustrated\u2026 - Estate of Jennifer Phipps - Mossgreen Auctions - Antiques Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=www.antiquesreporter.com.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abebooks.com/Pop-Novelty-Martin-Sharp-Draffin-Peter/30145627943/bd|title=Pop A Novelty by Peter Draffin, (Martin Sharp, illus.): (1967) {{!}} lamdha books|last=|first=|date=|website=www.abebooks.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nDraffin and Sharp formed a lasting association through their collaboration for ''Pop''. Draffin receives mention accordingly throughout Sharp's biographies by Lowell Tarling, to which he contributed commentary and interviews.<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" /><ref name=\"sharp2\" />\n\nWith Draffin still in Sydney, Sharp recalled illustrating ''Pop'' partly while \"tramping the [[hippie trail]] through Asia\" with [[Oz (magazine)|''Oz'']] magazine's [[Richard Neville (writer)|Richard Neville]].<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" />\n\nOnce ''Pop'' was in the printers, Draffin left Sydney to join [[Expatriate|expat]] Australian arts comrades in [[Swinging Sixties|Swinging London]], stopping en route on the Balearic island of [[Formentera|Formentara]].\n\nSharp, by then already London based but craving sunshine, joined Draffin as his houseguest on Formentara and began writing the poem that lyricised [[Tales of Brave Ulysses]], which Sharp later co-wrote for British rock band [[Cream (band)|Cream]].<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" />\n\nThe pair's houseguest roles were reversed for London. In an interview Draffin recalled being Sharpe's guest at [[The Pheasantry]] at 152 King's Road, Chelsea, before being moved out to accommodate [[Eric Clapton]].<ref name=\"abraxus2016\" />\n\nOthers living at The Pheasantry at around this time included [[David Litvinoff]] who worked in artist [[Timothy Whidborne|Tim Whidborne's]] studio there, writer [[Anthony Haden-Guest]], photographer [[Robert Whitaker (photographer)|Robert Whitaker]], and [[Germaine Greer]] who was writing ''[[The Female Eunuch]]'' in a room there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milesago.com/misc/sharp.htm|title=Martin Sharp|last=Weight|first=Greg|date=|website=MILESAGO|publisher=First published in Australian Artist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>Bell, Lynne (31 July 1969). \"Doctor who refuses to be type-cast\". ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. p. 19.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kleinhenz|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/germaine-the-life-of-germaine-greer/oclc/1046086370|title=Germaine: the life of Germaine Greer|date=2018|isbn=978-0-14-378284-1|language=English|oclc=1046086370}}</ref>\n\nLife at The Pheasantry placed Draffin and other residents at the epicentre of London's counter-cultural life.<ref>{{Cite book|last=D\u00e9charn\u00e9|first=Max|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/kings-road-the-rise-and-fall-of-the-hippest-street-in-the-world/oclc/954762096|title=King's Road: the rise and fall of the hippest street in the world|date=2005|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|isbn=978-0-297-84769-4|location=London|language=English|oclc=954762096}}</ref>\n\nAs an arts [[Counterculture of the 1960s|counterculture]] figure, Draffin was recognised as much as a face of the times as an author.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mellor|first=David|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/sixties-britain-and-france-1962-1973-the-utopian-years/oclc/56068696|title=The sixties: Britain and France, 1962-1973 : the utopian years|last2=Gervereau|first2=Laurent|date=1997|publisher=Philip Wilson ; Distributed in the USA and Canada by Antique Collectors' Club|year=|isbn=978-0-85667-467-9|location=London; Wappingers' Falls, NY|pages=(P. 25 Draffin photo)|oclc=56068696}}</ref> In that context he is mentioned in Yellow House co-founder [[George Gittoes]]' autobiography ''Blood Mystic'' (2016) and two Martin Sharp biographies.<ref name=\"gittoes2016\" /><ref name=\"abraxus2016\" /><ref name=\"sharp2\" />\n\nIn the late 1960s and early 1970s Draffin was a regular fiction contributor to [[K.G. Murray Publishing Company]]'s ''Man'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4535.htm|title=The FictionMags Index|last=|first=|date=|website=www.philsp.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philsp.com/data/data313.html#MAN|title=Man: Australian Magazine for Men|last=|first=|date=|website=www.philsp.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\"man2016\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/s/s2640.htm#A57340|title=Stories, Listed by Author|last=|first=|date=|website=www.philsp.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> He wrote feature articles for the [[Alternative culture|alternative]]/[[Underground press|underground]] magazine [[Oz (magazine)|''Oz'']] and lifestyle articles for [[Penthouse (magazine)|''Penthouse'']] magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1025&context=ozsydney|title=Oz Issue 26, March 1966|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Wollongong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"man2016\" /> He reviewed books for [[Phillip Frazer]]'s counterculture magazine ''Revolution.''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frazer|first=Phillip|date=1971-03-01|title=Revolution 2(2) March 1971|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/revolution/7|journal=Revolution|volume=|pages=|via=University of Wollongong}}</ref>\n\nThough some commentators have categorised Draffin as a [[Pulp magazine|pulp fiction]] writer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clintonwalker.com.au/lowest-of-the-low-8.html|title=Pulp Fiction|last=|first=|date=|website=Lowest of the Low, Clinton Walker|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://australianpulpfiction.blogspot.com/2008/08/who-are-these-people_21.html|title=Who are these people?|last=Ra|first=Jo|date=2008-08-21|website=A World of Australian Pulp Fiction|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> his body of work is eclectic and includes poetry, such as his 1968 ''A Dream of You''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C218211|title=A Dream of You {{!}} AustLit: Discover Australian Stories|last=Draffin|first=Peter: Australian Letters (periodical issue) vol. 8 no. 1, January 1968, pg. 67|date=|website=www.austlit.edu.au|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\nAs an Australian post-[[Beat Generation]] figure, Draffin became a favoured consultant and interviewee in later life, receiving credit from novelists and biographers researching the [[History of the hippie movement|hippie]] and counterculture scene.<ref name=\"sharp2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Lowell Tarling|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/1967-this-is-it/oclc/1142800905|title=1967 - This Is It|date=2020|publisher=ETT Imprint|year=|isbn=978-1-922384-13-3|location=S.l.|pages=|language=English|oclc=1142800905}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Burrough|first=C. S|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/or-forever-be-damned/oclc/896890074|title=Or forever be damned|date=2014|isbn=978-1-5008-6725-6|language=English|oclc=896890074}}</ref>\n\nDraffin was photographed with other notable Australians by Jon Lewis, for the [[Australian Bicentenary|Australian Bicentennial]] exhibition ''Face to Face \u2013 200 portraits 1986-1988'' which was purchased in 2001 by the [[National Museum of Australia]].<ref name=\"pete2008\">{{Cite web|url=http://collectionsearch.nma.gov.au/object/184760|title=Peter Draffin Portrait|last=|first=|date=|website=National Museum of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDraffin became teetotal for the last eighteen years of his life and still wrote daily, using manual typewriters, having always eschewed technology.<ref name=\"sharp2\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nHis ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]]'' tribute attracted Australian arts figures, including some from Draffin's halcyon days, to his [[Chippendale, New South Wales|Chippendale]] memorial service on 2 December 2019.<ref name=\"death2016\" />\n\nHis books remain in Australia's State and National Libraries, while his portrait remains with the National Museum of Australia.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Draffin|first=Peter|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/version/21842940|title=Pop|last2=Sharp|first2=Martin|date=1967|publisher=London ; Melbourne : Scripts|edition= 1st|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"pete2008\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.sl.nsw.gov.au/permalink/f/1ocrdrt/SLNSW_ALMA2196030090002626|title=Pop|last=Draffin|first=Peter|date=|website=State Library of New South Wales|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.slv.vic.gov.au/permalink/f/1cl35st/SLV_VOYAGER77093|title=Pop|last=Draffin|first=Peter|date=|website=State Library of Victoria|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://onesearch.slq.qld.gov.au/permalink/f/1oppkg1/slq_alma21128041070002061|title=Pop|last=Draffin|first=Peter|date=|website=State Library of Queensland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://collectionsearch.nma.gov.au/object/184760 National Museum of Australia portrait of Peter Draffin]\n* [https://tributes.smh.com.au/obituaries/108434/peter-francey-draffin/ ''Sydney Morning Herald'' obituary of Peter Draffin]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian writers]]\n[[Category:Australian novelists]]\n[[Category:Australian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Australian male writers]]\n[[Category:Australian male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "QLitBabel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Amended infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Draffin"}
{"title_page": "List of fact-checking websites", "text_new": "This '''list of fact-checking websites''' includes websites that provide [[fact-checking]] services about both political and non-political subjects.\n\nThe Reporters' Lab at [[Duke University]] maintains a database of fact-checking organizations that is managed by Mark Stencel and [[Bill Adair (journalist)|Bill Adair]]. The database tracks more than 100 non-partisan organizations around the world. The Lab's inclusion criteria is based on whether the organization\n\n{{quote|\n*examines all parties and sides;\n*examines discrete claims and reaches conclusions;\n*tracks political promises;\n*is transparent about sources and methods;\n*discloses funding/affiliations;\n*and whether its primary mission is news and information.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reporterslab.org/how-we-identify-fact-checkers/|title=How We Identify Fact-Checkers \u2013 Duke Reporters' Lab|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n== By region ==\n=== Africa ===\n\n* [[Africa Check]]:<ref>{{cite news|title=Nonpartisan Fact-Checking Comes to South Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/24/world/africa/nonpartisan-fact-checking-comes-to-south-africa.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Rick|last=Lyman|date=23 July 2013}}</ref> Africa's first independent fact-checking organisation with offices in Kenya, Nigeria, South Africa, Senegal and the UK checking claims made by public figures and the media in Africa.\n\n=== Asia ===\n'''Malaysia'''\n\n* [https://sebenarnya.my/ SEBENARNYA.MY] is a Malaysian fact-checking website set up by the [[Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission]].\n\n==== India ====\n[[International Fact Checking Network|International Fact-Checking Network]] ([https://ifcncodeofprinciples.poynter.org/ IFCN)] signatories:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ifcncodeofprinciples.poynter.org/signatories|title=IFCN Code of Principles|website=ifcncodeofprinciples.poynter.org|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n*[[Alt News]] is a fact-checking website.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Saurya|last1=Sengupta|accessdate=2020-04-09|title=On the origin of specious news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/society/on-the-origin-of-specious-news/article19184953.ece|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=1 July 2017|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n*WebQoof is ''[[The Quint]]''{{'}}s IFCN-certified fact-checking initiative.<ref>https://ifcncodeofprinciples.poynter.org/profile/the-quint</ref>\n*[https://www.boomlive.in/ BOOM] [https://hindi.boomlive.in/ BOOM Hindi] [https://bangla.boomlive.in/ BOOM Bangla] BOOM is an independent digital journalism initiative with a mission to fight misinformation and make the internet safer.\n*[https://www.vishvasnews.com/ Vishvas News] is a multilingual fact checking website\n*[https://www.factcrescendo.com/ Fact Crescendo] is a multilingual fact checking website, they also have a presence in Sri Lanka.\n*[https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check India Today - Fact Check] - is part of TV Today Network Ltd. The Fact Check section is part of the India Today website but this is managed separately and independently from the editorial operations of India Today.\n*[https://factly.in/ Factly]  FACTLY is one of the well known Data Journalism/Public Information portals in India. Each news story on FACTLY is backed by factual evidence/data from official sources that is either available in the public domain or that is collated/gathered/collected using tools such as the Right to Information (RTI).\n*[http://www.newsmobile.in/ NewsMobile] is a global fact-checker based in India.\n*[http://www.newschecker.in/ Newschecker.in] is a website to expose bias/agenda.\n*[http://factchecker.in/ FactChecker.in] is scrutinizing claims made in public.\n\nNot on IFCN list of signatories:\n\n*[http://smhoaxslayer.com/ SMHoaxSlayer] is a broad spectrum fact-checking website with verifying social media hoaxes and scams circulating in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|title=This 'Hoax Slayer' has busted 1,300 fake forwards on WhatsApp|date=1 April 2017|work=YourStory.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/videos/lifestyle/fake-news-warriors/video-nWiuKLDlU2nDOvEZmeaj9L.html|title=Fake News Warriors|date=2017-07-08|website=hindustantimes.com/|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/more-lifestyle/in-an-era-of-fake-news-check-out-india-s-homegrown-hoax-slayer/story-zyonebYJ4ApaOxABOybvSN.html|title=In an era of fake news, check out India's homegrown Hoax Slayer|date=13 January 2017|work=hindustantimes.com/|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://factordaily.com/boom-live-fake-news/|title=Boom! This team of four journalists is on a mission to hunt down and destroy fake news in India {{!}} FactorDaily|date=28 July 2017|work=FactorDaily|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref>\n*[https://www.indiaspend.com/ IndiaSpend] is a non-profit, data-driven and fact checking website founded in 2011. In March 2014 they launched FactChecker.in <ref>https://www.factchecker.in/about-us/</ref>\n\n==== Japan ====\n* [http://gohoo.org/ GoHoo]: Launched by a nonprofit association Watchdog for Accuracy in News-reporting, Japan (WANJ or \u4e00\u822c\u793e\u56e3\u6cd5\u4eba [[:ja: \u65e5\u672c\u5831\u9053\u691c\u8a3c\u6a5f\u69cb|\u65e5\u672c\u5831\u9053\u691c\u8a3c\u6a5f\u69cb]]) on November 16, 2014. Crowd-funded approx. 1.6 million yen through Ready For.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u79c1\u305f\u3061\u306f\u3001\u30de\u30b9\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u306e\u60c5\u5831\u306e\u771f\u507d\u3092\u30c1\u30a7\u30c3\u30af\u3059\u308b\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u3001\u300c\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u306e\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u300d\u3092\u5275\u308a\u307e\u3059\uff01 |url=https://readyfor.jp/projects/gohoo |publisher=Ready For |accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref> Awarded Social Business Grand Prize 2012 Summer.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u30bd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d3\u30b8\u30cd\u30b9\u30b0\u30e9\u30f3\u30d7\u30ea 2012\u590f \u7d50\u679c\u767a\u8868 |url=https://socialvalue.jp/final/2012summer/index.html |publisher=Social Entrepreneur School |accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref>\n* [http://jcej.info/ Japan Center of Education for Journalists (JCEJ)]: Fosters journalists and fact-checkers by referring to a ''Journalist's Guide to Social Sources'' published by [https://firstdraftnews.com/ First Draft News], a project of the Harvard Kennedy School's Shorenstein Center. JCEJ itself also debunks falsehoods.<ref name=\"Nieman-Japan\">{{cite web |last=Kajimoto |first=Masato |title=A snap election (and global worries over fake news) spur fact-checking collaborations in Japan |url=http://www.niemanlab.org/2017/10/a-snap-election-and-global-worries-over-fake-news-spur-fact-checking-collaborations-in-japan/ |publisher=Nieman Foundation at Harvard |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref>\n\n====Taiwan====\n*[https://tfc-taiwan.org.tw/ \u53f0\u7063\u4e8b\u5be6\u67e5\u6838\u4e2d\u5fc3] (Taiwan Fact-checking Center)\n\n=== Australia ===\n* RMIT ABC Fact Check:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/factcheck/ | title=RMIT ABC Fact Check | accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> An IFCN-accredited fact checking organisation, launched in 2017, jointly funded by [[RMIT University]] and the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/factcheck/about/ | title=About | publisher=RMIT ABC Fact Check | accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Europe ===\n====Armenia====\n* Fip.am (https://fip.am/), launched by the NGO \"Union of Informed Citizens\" (UIC) in 2016 as Sut.am and renamed in September 2018<ref>https://fip.am/3783</ref>\n\n====Austria====\n* Mimikama:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mimikama.at |title=Mimikama \u2013 Verein zur Aufkl\u00e4rung \u00fcber Internetmissbrauch|publisher=Mimikama \u2013 Verein zur Aufkl\u00e4rung \u00fcber Internetmissbrauch|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> Austrian fact-checking website which mainly focuses on Facebook hoaxes in the German and Dutch language area.\n\n====Croatia====\n*[[Faktograf.hr]]:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrt.hr/305623/vijesti/faktografhr-u-lazi-uhvaceni-suker-bauk-i-grabar-kitarovic |title=Faktograf.hr - evo koji su politi\u010dari uhva\u0107eni u la\u017ei |trans-title=Faktograf.hr - here are the politicians who were caught lying |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 October 2015 |website=HRT |publisher= |access-date=10 November 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Croatian fact-checking website set up by the [[Croatian Journalists' Association]] and [[GONG (organization)|GONG]].\n\n====Finland====\n* [https://faktabaari.fi/ Faktabaari]:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-7885770|title=Faktabaari paljastaa poliitikkojen puppupuheet|accessdate=21 November 2019|work= Yleisradio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hs.fi/kulttuuri/art-2000005917242.html|title=Faktabaari sai Chydeniuksen avoimuuspalkinnon| date=30 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2019|newspaper=Helsingin Sanomat, hs.fi}}</ref> a Finnish awarded and politically independent fact-checking website, launched in 2014.\n\n====France====\n* Les D\u00e9codeurs:<ref>{{cite news|title=Fact-checking blogs turn up heat on French candidates|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20120223-france-presidential-elections-blogs-fact-checking-candidates-truth-lies-journalism|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=France 24}}</ref> French fact-checking blog run by ''[[Le Monde]]''.\n*[https://factuel.afp.com/ Factuel]: French fact-checking blog run by the [[Agence France-Presse]].\n*[https://captainfact.io/ CaptainFact]: French collaborative fact-checking platform.\n\n==== Georgia ====\n* FactCheck Georgia:<ref>{{cite news |title= FactCheck Georgia |url= https://factcheck.ge/en |accessdate= 2 February 2019 |work= factcheck.ge |language= en}}</ref> a project of the Tbilisi-based think-tank Georgia's Reforms Associates (GRASS), launched in 2013.<ref name=\"DNR\">{{cite news |last1= Graves |first1= Lucas |last2= Cherubini |first2= Federica |title= The Rise of Fact-Checking Sites in Europe |url= http://www.digitalnewsreport.org/publications/2016/rise-fact-checking-sites-europe/ |accessdate=2 February 2019 |work=Digital News Report |date=2016}}</ref>\n<!--  <references />  -->\n\n====Germany====\n* volksverpetzer.de (https://www.volksverpetzer.de/), launched by Thomas Laschyk\n\n====Greece====\n* Ellinikahoaxes.gr:<ref>{{cite news|title=\u039c\u03b9\u03bb\u03ae\u03c3\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u039a\u03c5\u03bd\u03b7\u03b3\u03ac\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1 Hoaxes \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u038a\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bd\u03b5\u03c4|url=https://www.vice.com/gr/article/ez45gp/o-ellinas-kinigos-tis-alithias|accessdate=20 December 2017|newspaper=Vice Greece|date=24 November 2016}}</ref> a Greek fact-checking website launched in 2013. Debunks hoaxes, urban legends, fake news, internet scams and other stories of questionable origin.\n* Factchecker.gr:<ref>{{cite news|title=\u03a4\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u0392\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03b7;|url=http://mikropragmata.lifo.gr/zoi/enas-eisangeleas-mporei-na-koitaksei-zitima-aftis-tis-kyrias/|accessdate=20 December 2017|newspaper=Lifo|date=11 December 2017}}</ref> an independent Greek fact-checking website launched in February 2017 specializing in pseudoscience and medical frauds.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03b4\u03c1\u03ac\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0392\u03cc\u03bb\u03bf \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf \u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae|url=http://www.taxydromos.gr/Topika/262158-antidraseis-ston-bolo-gia-proskeklhmeno-omilhth.html|accessdate=20 December 2017|newspaper=\u03a4\u03b1\u03c7\u03c5\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2|date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Italy====\n* Bufale.net:<ref>{{cite news|title=Come smascherare le notizie false e le bufale che girano su internet|url= https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/blog/bufalenet/|accessdate=20 December 2017|newspaper=Il Fatto Quotidiano|date=18 December 2016}}</ref> Italian national fact-checking service website and creators of the first antifakenews addon for Chrome\n* Pagella Politica:<ref>{{cite news|title=Italian politics: Pinocchio's heirs|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/charlemagne/2013/02/italian-politics-1|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=The Economist|date=22 February 2013}}</ref> an Italian fact-checking website.\n\n====Moldova====\n* [https://stopfals.md/ro/ Stopfals.md]: launched by Association of Independent Press (API) from the Republic of Moldova in 2017\n\n====Norway====\n* Faktisk.no: Fact-checking site focusing on public debate in [[Norway]]. Set up by rival Norwegian media outlets and a part of [[Poynter Institute|IFCN]] <ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.poynter.org/fact-checking/2017/rivals-become-partners-in-norways-newest-fact-checking-project/|title=Rivals become partners in Norway's newest fact-checking project|last=Mantzarlis|first=Alexios|date=22 March 2017|work=Poynter Institute|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Poland====\n*Demagog:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.demagog.org.pl/|title=Demagog|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> First fact-checking website in Poland, dedicated to fact check political statements. Member of International Fact-Checking Network at Poynter Institute.\n*Fakenews.pl:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fakenews.pl/|title=Fakenews.pl|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> a Polish fact-checking website.\n*[[OKO.press]]:<ref name=\"France24_acclaimed\">{{cite news | title=Poland's LGBT community under fire ahead of elections | date=2019-10-08 |newspaper=[[France 24]] | url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191008-poland-s-lgbt-community-under-fire-ahead-of-elections |accessdate=2020-03-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008081038/https://www.france24.com/en/20191008-poland-s-lgbt-community-under-fire-ahead-of-elections |archivedate= 2019-10-08 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> an investigative journalism website in Poland created in 2016.\n\n====Portugal====\n*Observador:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.observador.pt/|title=Observador|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> First newspaper in Portugal with fact-checking section. First Portuguese member of International Fact-Checking Network at Poynter Institute.\n\n====Romania====\n*Factual.ro:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.factual.ro/|title=Factual|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> First fact-checking website in Romania, dedicated to fact check political statements. Set up by the Funky Citizens NGO.\n\n====Spain====\n* Miniver.org:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://miniver.org |title=Miniver.org |publisher=Miniver.org |date=20 May 2017 |accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref> First dedicated fact-checking web in Spain, launched in 2017, with the purpose of debunking fake news. Accredited by Google as fact-checking organization.\n* Newtral:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newtral.es |title=Newtral |publisher=Newtral.es |date=10 October 2019 |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> Spanish fact-checking organization which aims to empower people to draw their own conclusions by analysing public discourse.\n\n====Ukraine====\n* VoxCheck:<ref>{{cite news |title= VoxUkraine |url= https://voxukraine.org/en/category/voxcheck/ |accessdate= 2 February 2019 |work= VoxUkraine.org |language= en}}</ref> unveiled by VoxUkraine, an online economics and policy project, in 2015.<ref name=\"DNR\"/>\n* FactCheck Ukraine: launched by the Kyiv-based Ukrainian Team of Reformers in 2016.<ref name=\"DNR\"/>\n* Stopfake.org:<ref>{{cite news |title= About us |url= https://www.stopfake.org/en/about-us/ |accessdate= 2 February 2019 |work= StopFake.org |date= 21 May 2018}}</ref> launched by the Kyiv Mohyla Journalism School in 2014.\n\n====United Kingdom====\n* [[BBC News|BBC]] Reality Check<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/jan/12/bbc-sets-up-team-to-debunk-fake-news|title= BBC sets up team to debunk fake news|last= Jackson|first=Jasper|date=12 January 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=16 September 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n* [[Full Fact]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://FullFact.org |title=Full Fact |publisher=FullFact.org |date=15 February 2012 |accessdate=15 February 2012}}</ref> An independent fact-checking organisation based in the UK which aims to \"promote accuracy in public debate\", launched in 2009.\n* FactCheckNI:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://factcheckni.org |title=FactCheckNI |publisher=FactCheckNI.org |date=29 November 2019 |accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> The first independent dedicated fact-checking service for Northern Ireland, launched in 2016, checking claims as well as offering training in critical thinking, tools and techniques any member of the public can use.\n* The FactCheck blog:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.channel4.com/factcheck/ |title=The FactCheck Blog |publisher= Channel 4 |date=15 February 2012 |accessdate=15 February 2012}}</ref> A fact-checking blog run by the [[Channel 4 News]] organization in the UK.\n* [[The Ferret (news)|Ferret]] Fact Service:<ref>{{cite web|url= https://theferret.scot/category/fact-check/|title= Ferret Fact Service|last= |first= |date= 4 April 2017|website= |accessdate= }}</ref> Scotland's first fact-checker launched in April 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journalism.co.uk/news/the-ferret-launches-fact-checking-service-aiming-to-work-with-its-community-to-verify-claims/s2/a703378/|title=Journalism.co.uk interview|last=|first=|date=28 April 2017|website=|accessdate=}}</ref> after a grant from the Google Digital News Initiative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digitalnewsinitiative.com/dni-projects/ferret-fact-check/|title=Google DNI: The Ferret|date=19 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018172909/https://digitalnewsinitiative.com/dni-projects/ferret-fact-check/|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Latin America ===\n\n* [[Argentina]]: [https://chequeado.com/ ''Chequeado.com'']<ref>{{cite news|title=Chequeado.com: Fiel defensor de los hechos|url=http://blogs.lanacion.com.ar/data/argentina/chequeadocom-fiel-defensor-de-los-hechos/|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=Lanacion.com}}</ref>\n* [[Brazil]]: [https://piaui.folha.uol.com.br/lupa Ag\u00eancia Lupa],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://exame.abril.com.br/tecnologia/programa-do-facebook-de-checagem-de-noticias-chega-ao-brasil/|title=Programa do Facebook de checagem de not\u00edcias chega ao Brasil|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2018-05-10|newspaper=EXAME}}</ref> [https://aosfatos.org Aos Fatos],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogdomariomagalhaes.blogosfera.uol.com.br/2015/07/09/aos-fatos-um-servico-jornalistico-para-checar-o-que-e-fato-ou-cascata|title='Aos Fatos': um servi\u00e7o jornal\u00edstico para checar o que \u00e9 fato ou cascata|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2015-07-09|website=Blog do M\u00e1rio Magalh\u00e3es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brasil.googleblog.com/2017/02/seloverificacaodefatos.html|title=\nSelo de verifica\u00e7\u00e3o de fatos chega \u00e0 Am\u00e9rica Latina|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2017-02-15|website=O Blog do Google Brasil}}</ref> [https://www.boatos.org/ Boatos],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factcheckingday.com/articles/14/16-ways-fact-checkers-and-users-can-debunk-hoaxes-on-whatsapp|title=16 ways fact-checkers and users can debunk hoaxes on WhatsApp|accessdate=2018-12-07|website=International Fact-Checking Day}}</ref> [https://projetocomprova.com.br/ Comprova],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dc.clicrbs.com.br/sc/noticias/noticia/2018/06/projeto-comprova-une-redacoes-do-brasil-para-combater-noticias-falsas-nas-eleicoes-10390637.html|title=Projeto Comprova une reda\u00e7\u00f5es do Brasil para combater not\u00edcias falsas nas elei\u00e7\u00f5es|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2018-06-28|website=Di\u00e1rio Catarinense}}</ref> [https://blogs.oglobo.globo.com/eissomesmo/ ''\u00c9 isso Mesmo?'']<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oglobo.globo.com/brasil/grupo-vai-checar-combater-avanco-de-noticias-falsas-21048776|title=Grupo vai checar e combater avan\u00e7o de not\u00edcias falsas|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2017-03-12|website=O Globo}}</ref> (from [[O Globo]]), [http://www.e-farsas.com E-farsas],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tecmundo.com.br/internet/60781-entrevistamos-criador-farsas-o-site-desvenda-boatos-internet.htm|title=Entrevistamos o criador do E-farsas, site que desvenda os boatos da internet!|last=|first=|date=2018-01-01|website=Tec Mundo|access-date=}}</ref> [http://www.ebc.com.br/hoax ''Portal EBC's Hoax reports''],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/polis/2018/03/08/features-and-challenges-of-latin-american-fact-checkers/|title=Fact-checking in Latin America: features and challenges|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2018-03-08|website=Polis - journalism and society at the LSE}}</ref> [http://apublica.org/truco-no-congresso Truco no Congresso],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://congressoemfoco.uol.com.br/especial/noticias/truco-no-congresso-chegou-a-hora-da-verdade|title=Truco no Congresso: chegou a hora da verdade|accessdate=2018-12-07|date=2015-08-03|website=Congresso em Foco}}</ref> [https://noticias.uol.com.br/confere ''UOL Confere'']<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mundoeducacao.bol.uol.com.br/curiosidades/fake-news.htm|title=Fake News|accessdate=2018-12-07|website=Mundo Educa\u00e7\u00e3o \u2013 Educa\u00e7\u00e3o, Vestibular, ENEM, Trabalhos Escolares}}</ref>\n* [[Chile]]: [http://www.chvnoticias.cl/chilecheck/ ChileCheck],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2017/10/06/creador-del-programa-chile-check-devela-5-mentiras-de-los-candidato