bel": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mid-York_Colorguard_Circuit"}
{"title_page": "List of films about the American Revolution", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of films and TV films about the [[American Revolution]]'''.\n\nA Canadian historian has evaluated twelve Hollywood films featuring the American Revolution from 1939\u20132002. She compares the fictional versus the scholarly components of popular entertainment as they impact the treatment of heroes and villains, Patriots and Loyalists, social structure and social conflicts. She compares cinematic understandings of the Revolution with the interpretations of historians to reveal thematic consistencies, variations, and conceptual gulfs between filmmakers and historians.<ref>Nancy L. Rhoden, \"Patriots, Villains, and the Quest for Liberty: How American Film has Depicted the American Revolution.\" ''Canadian Review of American Studies'' 37.2 (2007): 205-238.</ref>\n{{Dynamic list}}\n\n* 1776, or ''[[The Hessian Renegades]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1909 film by [[D.W. Griffith]]\n* ''[[1776 (musical)|1776]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1972 film starring [[William Daniels]], [[Howard Da Silva]], [[Ken Howard]], [[Donald Madden]] and [[John Cullum]]. Directed by [[Peter H. Hunt]].\n* ''[[Alexander Hamilton (film)|Alexander Hamilton]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1931 film starring [[George Arliss]] and Directed by [[John G. Adolfi]].\n* ''[[America (1924 film)|America]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1924 film; epic directed by [[D.W. Griffith]] and starring [[Lionel Barrymore]].<ref>Lawrence L. Murray, \"History at the Movies during the Sesquicentennial: DW Griffith's America (1924).\" ''Historian'' 41.3 (1979): 450-466.  [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1540-6563.1979.tb00554.x/full excerpt]</ref>\n* ''[[April Morning]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1987 starring [[Chad Lowe]], [[Tommy Lee Jones]], and [[Robert Urich]].\n* ''[[Benedict Arnold: A Question of Honor]]''&nbsp;\u2013 2003 film starring: [[Aidan Quinn]] as [[Benedict Arnold]] and [[Kelsey Grammer]] as George Washington.<ref>Suzanne Broderick, \"Review\" [https://muse.jhu.edu/article/396088/summary  ''Film & History'' 33#2 (2003) pp. 72-74 online]</ref>\n* ''[[Beyond the Mask]]''&nbsp;\u20132015 film\n* ''[[Cardigan (film)|Cardigan]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1922 film\n* ''[[Drums Along the Mohawk]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1939 film starring: [[Claudette Colbert]] and [[Henry Fonda]]; Directed by [[John Ford]]\n* ''[[Independence (1976 film)|Independence]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1976 docudrama film directed by [[John Huston]], narrated by [[E. G. Marshall]] and starring [[Eli Wallach]], [[Pat Hingle]], [[Ken Howard]] and [[Anne Jackson]]; shown continuously at Philadelphia's [[Independence Visitor Center]].\n* ''[[John Adams (miniseries)|John Adams]]'' is a television miniseries that was aired on [[HBO]] in 2008.  The miniseries was directed by [[Tom Hooper]] and starred [[Paul Giamatti]] as John Adams and [[Laura Linney]] as [[Abigail Adams]].  The miniseries takes place before, during, and after the [[American Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/john-adams/about/index.html|title=John Adams|website=HBO}}</ref>\n* ''[[John Paul Jones (film)|John Paul Jones]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1959 film directed by [[John Farrow]], starring [[Robert Stack]] and [[Charles Coburn]]\n* ''[[Johnny Tremain]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1957 film adaptation of the 1943 [[Esther Forbes]] novel starring [[Hal Stalmaster]] and, among others, [[Walter Coy]]. Directed by [[Robert Stevenson (director)|Robert Stevenson]]\n* ''[[La Fayette (film)|La Fayette]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1961 film\n* ''[[Liberty's Kids]]'' \u2013 2002\u20132004 [[PBS]] animated series.<ref>Andrew M. Schocket, \"Little Founders on the Small Screen: Interpreting a Multicultural American Revolution for Children's Television.\" ''Journal of American Studies'' 45.1 (2011): 145-163. [https://scholarworks.bgsu.edu/hist_pub/1 online]</ref>\n* ''[[Revolution (1985 film)|Revolution]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1985 film starring [[Al Pacino]]. Directed by [[Hugh Hudson]]<ref name=\"Melvyn Stokes\">Melvyn Stokes, ''American History Through Hollywood Film: From the Revolution to the 1960s'' (2013) ch 1.</ref>\n* ''Scouting for Washington''&nbsp;\u2013 1917 Edison Studios\n* ''[[Sons of Liberty (film)|Sons of Liberty]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1939 film starring: [[Claude Rains]], [[Gale Sondergaard]]; Director: [[Michael Curtiz]].\n* ''[[Sons of Liberty (miniseries)|Sons of Liberty]]''&nbsp;\u2013 2015 miniseries starring [[Ben Barnes (actor)|Ben Barnes]], [[Rafe Spall]], [[Henry Thomas]], [[Dean Norris]] and [[Jason O'Mara]]; Director: [[Kari Skogland]]; produced for broadcast by [[The History Channel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/shows/sons-of-liberty/about|title=About Sons of Liberty \u2013 HISTORY}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Crossing (2000 film)|The Crossing]]''&nbsp;\u2013 2000 film starring: [[Jeff Daniels]], [[Roger Rees]], Director: [[Robert Harmon]]; screenwriter [[Howard Fast]] based on his novel; produced for broadcast by the Arts and Entertainment cable television network\n* ''[[The Devil's Disciple (1959 film)|The Devil's Disciple]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1959 film adaptation of the play by [[George Bernard Shaw]]; starring [[Burt Lancaster]], [[Kirk Douglas]], and [[Laurence Olivier]]. Directed by [[Guy Hamilton]]\n* ''[[The Devil's Disciple (1987 film)|The Devil's Disciple]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1987 TV film adaptation of the play by [[George Bernard Shaw]]; starring: [[Patrick Stewart]], Director: [[David Jones (director)|David Jones]]\n* ''[[The Howards of Virginia]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1940 Starring: Cary Grant, Director: Frank Lloyd\n* ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]''&nbsp;\u2013 2000 film starring: [[Mel Gibson]], [[Heath Ledger]], Director: [[Roland Emmerich]]<ref>Mark Glancy,  \"The war of independence in feature films: The Patriot (2000) and the 'special relationship' between Hollywood and Britain.\" ''Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television'' 25.4 (2005): 523-545.</ref><ref name=\"Melvyn Stokes\" />\n* ''[[The Pursuit of Happiness (1934 film)|The Pursuit of Happiness]]'' - 1934 film\n* ''[[The Rebels (film)|The Rebels]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1979 TV miniseries based on the novel by [[John Jakes]], starring [[Andrew Stevens]]\n* ''[[The Scarlet Coat]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1955 film directed by John Sturges, focuses on [[Benedict Arnold]]\n* ''[[The Spirit of '76 (1917 film)|The Spirit of '76]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1917 film<ref name=\"Melvyn Stokes\" />\n* ''[[The Time of Their Lives]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1946, [[Abbott and Costello]] Comedy. Directed by [[Charles Barton (director)|Charles Barton]].\n* ''[[Turn: Washington's Spies]]'' \u2013 2014\u201317 [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series<ref>See [http://www.amc.com/shows/turn AMC website for \"Turn\"]</ref><ref>Carolyn Eastman, \"The Revolution Takes a Turn: AMC's Drama about Washington's Spies Aims for Moral Complexity\"  ''Perspectives on History'' (April 2014). [https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/april-2014/the-revolution-takes-a-turn online]</ref>\n<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[File:1776-musical.jpg|thumb|250px]] -->\n* ''[[Washington (miniseries)|Washington]]'' is a 6-hour television miniseries that was aired on [[The History Channel]] in 2020.  The miniseries was directed by [[Matthew Ginsburg]] and starred [[Nicholas Rowe (actor)|Nicholas Rowe]] as George Washington and is narrated by [[Jeff Daniels]]. The series covers the life of George Washington from his birth to his passing at age 67.  \n* ''[[Where Do We Go from Here? (1945 film)|Where Do We Go from Here?]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1945, Comedy. Directed by [[Gregory Ratoff]], starring [[Fred MacMurray]].\n* ''[[Williamsburg: the Story of a Patriot]]''&nbsp;\u2013 1957 film shown at Colonial Williamsburg continually since 1957. Directed by [[George Seaton]], starring [[Jack Lord]].\n\n\n== See also ==\n* [[British Empire in fiction]]\n* [[Commemoration of the American Revolution]]\n* [[Historical drama]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Glancy,