idzka]]\n[[Category:Polish Jews]]\n[[Category:United States National Medal of Arts recipients]]\n[[Category:Directors of Palme d'Or winners]]\n[[Category:AFI Life Achievement Award recipients]]\n", "name_user": "Cowlibob", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Wilder"}
{"title_page": "DB Schenker", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = DB Schenker\n| logo = [[File:DB Schenker logo.svg|frameless]]\n| type = [[Logistics]], [[freight transport]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = Schenker Stinnes Logistics\n| successor = \n| foundation = \n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Essen]]\n| location_country = [[Germany]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dbschenker.com/global/about | title= About DB Schenker}}</ref>\n| location = \n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{unbulleted list|Jochen Thewes<br><small>(CEO)</small><br>Oliver Seidl<br><small>(CFO)</small>|Thorsten Meincke<br><small>(COO Air & Ocean)<br>\n</small></small>|Christian Drenthen<br><small>(COO Land Transport)</small>|[[Xavier Garijo]]<br><small>(Board Member Contract Logistics)</small>|Markus Sontheimer<br><small>(CIO/CDO)</small>|Thomas Schulz<br><small>(CHRO)</small>}}\n| industry = \n| products = Transportation and logistics\n| services = \n| revenue = \u20ac16.4&nbsp;billion<ref>{{cite web | url=https://ir.deutschebahn.com/en/db-group/at-a-glance/key-figures/key-figures-2017 | title=Key Figures 2017 Deutsche Bahn IR | publisher=Deutsche Bahn AG | accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 72,000<ref name=profile>{{cite web | url=https://www.dbschenker.com/global/about | title= About DB Schenker}}</ref>\n| parent = [[Deutsche Bahn AG]]\n| divisions = Land Transport, Air Freight, Ocean Freight, Contract Logistics, Lead Logistics\n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|www.dbschenker.com|DB Schenker}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n{{see also| Schenker AG}}\n'''DB Schenker''' is a division of [[Rail transport in Germany|German rail]] operator [[Deutsche Bahn AG]] that focuses on [[logistics]]. The company was acquired by Deutsche Bahn as Schenker-Stinnes in 2002. It comprises divisions for air, land, sea freight, and Contract Logistics. Its to bad though that this is the worst and slowest logistics company in europe.\n\n==History==\nIn his biography, then CEO of Deutsche Bahn Hartmut Mehdorn justified the acquisition of international logistics companies with customer demands. In 2000, analysis had shown the 200 largest customers ship up to 60% of their freight abroad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.deutschebahn.com/fileadmin/Deutsch/2001/Berichte/2001_gb_dbkonzern_de.pdf|title=Gesch\u00e4ftsbericht 2001 (p. 13)|date=April 23, 2002|website=Deutsche Bahn IR|access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>. Since the core operating territory had been Germany, customers were lost to competitors with a more compelling international offer. There was no time to grow organically in such markets<ref name=\"mehdorn-2007-114\">Hartmut Mehdorn: ''\u00abDiplomat wollte ich nie werden\u00bb''. Hoffmann und Campe, Berlin 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-455-50047-9}}, p.&nbsp;114.</ref>. This analysis led to the acquisition of Stinnes AG and the associated brand name Schenker. \nSince December 2007 DB Schenker has been the freight logistics subsidiary of [[Deutsche Bahn]]. DB Schenker combines all transport and logistic activities of Deutsche Bahn (except rail cargo), employing over 72000 staff spread across about 2,000 locations in about 140 countries.\n<!-- \nThe below statement would fit better into the DB Cargo page; no relevance for DB Schenker operations or history\nSince 2016, the UK operation has operated under the [[DB Cargo UK]] brand name. DB Schenker now is the biggest freight operator in the [[United Kingdom]], and also operates the [[British Royal Train]] used by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and the [[British royal family|Royal Family]].<ref>[http://uk.dbcargo.com/rail-uk-en/News_Media/news/10867046/new_brand.html The UK's leading rail freight company announces rebrand] DB Cargo UK 2 March 2016</ref>-->\n\n== Organization ==\n[[Schenker AG]] and its many subsidiaries handle worldwide logistics operations including Land Transport, Air and Ocean Freight as well as Contract Logistics/SCM, and is part of the DB Schenker organization. Since 2016, rail freight business no longer operates under the brand ''DB Schenker Rail.'' Instead, it operates as a standalone business unit under the brand name ''DB Cargo'' in Deutsche Bahn Group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.deutschebahn.com/en/db-group/business-units/db-cargo/|title=DB Cargo|website=Deutsche Bahn IR|language=en|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>.  \n\n== Key Customers ==\nDB Schenker serves many global and local firms across all industries. Notably, DB Schenker manages large and complex supply chains for multinationals such as [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lloydsloadinglist.com/freight-directory/news/DB-Schenker-to-manage-new-Apple-distribution-centre-in-India/68156.htm|title=DB Schenker to manage new Apple distribution centre in India - Lloyd's Loading List|website=www.lloydsloadinglist.com|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[Procter & Gamble]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/procter-gamble-is-latest-to-take-over-inland-warehouse-shifting-500-plus-schenker-staff|title=Procter & Gamble is latest to take over Inland warehouse, shifting 500-plus Schenker staff|date=2019-03-04|website=Press Enterprise|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[Dell]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbschenker.com/au-en/about/press/db-schenker-news/hoxton-park-grand-opening-510154|title=Hoxton Park Grand Opening|website=DB Schenker|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[ASML Holding|ASML]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbschenker.com/cn-en/about/press/corporate-news/opening-aslms-tss-centre-524518|title=Grand Opening of ASML's TSS Center operated by DB Schenker|website=DB Schenker|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[BMW]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbschenker.com/de-de/ueber-uns/presse-center/db-schenker-news/db-befoerdert-2016-ueber-40-000-container-zwischen-china-und-deutschland-13834|title=DB bef\u00f6rdert 2016 \u00fcber 40.000 Container zwischen China und Deutschland|website=DB Schenker|language=de-DE|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref> and many more.\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn 2016, DB Schenker was convicted for consecutive cases of corruption in St. Petersburg, Russia, bribing local customs officials from 2010 to mid-2012. At the time, DB Schenker involved a Russian agency for enabling the rapid flow of shipments to carmaker Ford\u2019s St. Petersburg facility. DB Schenker had to pay a penalty of \u20ac2m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cargoforwarder.eu/2016/11/06/db-schenker-convicted-of-bribery/|title=DB Schenker Convicted of Bribery|date=2016-11-06|website=CargoForwarder Global|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>.\n\nIn September 2015, then and current CEO Jochen Thewes slapped and pushed a cab driver, who refused to pick up a drunken Thewes, in downtown Singapore. He also kicked the car and caused damage. Thewes was eventually sentenced to a fine of S$1000 and two weeks of jailtime in Singapore<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ceo-gets-jail-for-slapping-cabby|title=CEO gets jail for slapping cabby|date=2016-09-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2020, DB Schenker was accused of unfair price dumping during the [[Coronavirus recession]] and related market turbulences. Using its status as a state-owned company (as subsidiary of [[Deutsche Bahn]]), it offered prices below its own production costs for some European land routes via the freight exchange [[Timocom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurotransport.de/artikel/frachten-weiter-unter-druck-db-schenker-lockt-mit-billigpreisen-11156752.html|title=Frachten weiter unter Druck: DB Schenker lockt mit Billigpreisen|last=Rathmann|first=Matthias|date=2020-04-08|website=Eurotransport|language=de|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gottfried Schenker]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Deutsche Bahn}}\n\n[[Category:Logistics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Bahn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = DB Schenker\n| logo = [[File:DB Schenker logo.svg|frameless]]\n| type = [[Logistics]], [[freight transport]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = Schenker Stinnes Logistics\n| successor = \n| foundation = \n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Essen]]\n| location_country = [[Germany]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dbschenker.com/global/about | title= About DB Schenker}}</ref>\n| location = \n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{unbulleted list|Jochen Thewes<br><small>(CEO)</small><br>Oliver Seidl<br><small>(CFO)</small>|Thorsten Meincke<br><small>(COO Air & Ocean)<br>\n</small></small>|Christian Drenthen<br><small>(COO Land Transport)</small>|[[Xavier Garijo]]<br><small>(Board Member Contract Logistics)</small>|Markus Sontheimer<br><small>(CIO/CDO)</small>|Thomas Schulz<br><small>(CHRO)</small>}}\n| industry = \n| products = Transportation and logistics\n| services = \n| revenue = \u20ac16.4&nbsp;billion<ref>{{cite web | url=https://ir.deutschebahn.com/en/db-group/at-a-glance/key-figures/key-figures-2017 | title=Key Figures 2017 Deutsche Bahn IR | publisher=Deutsche Bahn AG | accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 72,000<ref name=profile>{{cite web | url=https://www.dbschenker.com/global/about | title= About DB Schenker}}</ref>\n| parent = [[Deutsche Bahn AG]]\n| divisions = Land Transport, Air Freight, Ocean Freight, Contract Logistics, Lead Logistics\n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|www.dbschenker.com|DB Schenker}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n{{see also| Schenker AG}}\n'''DB Schenker''' is a division of [[Rail transport in Germany|German rail]] operator [[Deutsche Bahn AG]] that focuses on [[logistics]]. The company was acquired by Deutsche Bahn as Schenker-Stinnes in 2002. It comprises divisions for air, land, sea freight, and Contract Logistics.\n\n==History==\nIn his biography, then CEO of Deutsche Bahn Hartmut Mehdorn justified the acquisition of international logistics companies with customer demands. In 2000, analysis had shown the 200 largest customers ship up to 60% of their freight abroad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.deutschebahn.com/fileadmin/Deutsch/2001/Berichte/2001_gb_dbkonzern_de.pdf|title=Gesch\u00e4ftsbericht 2001 (p. 13)|date=April 23, 2002|website=Deutsche Bahn IR|access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>. Since the core operating territory had been Germany, customers were lost to competitors with a more compelling international offer. There was no time to grow organically in such markets<ref name=\"mehdorn-2007-114\">Hartmut Mehdorn: ''\u00abDiplomat wollte ich nie werden\u00bb''. Hoffmann und Campe, Berlin 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-455-50047-9}}, p.&nbsp;114.</ref>. This analysis led to the acquisition of Stinnes AG and the associated brand name Schenker. \nSince December 2007 DB Schenker has been the freight logistics subsidiary of [[Deutsche Bahn]]. DB Schenker combines all transport and logistic activities of Deutsche Bahn (except rail cargo), employing over 72000 staff spread across about 2,000 locations in about 140 countries.\n<!-- \nThe below statement would fit better into the DB Cargo page; no relevance for DB Schenker operations or history\nSince 2016, the UK operation has operated under the [[DB Cargo UK]] brand name. DB Schenker now is the biggest freight operator in the [[United Kingdom]], and also operates the [[British Royal Train]] used by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and the [[British royal family|Royal Family]].<ref>[http://uk.dbcargo.com/rail-uk-en/News_Media/news/10867046/new_brand.html The UK's leading rail freight company announces rebrand] DB Cargo UK 2 March 2016</ref>-->\n\n== Organization ==\n[[Schenker AG]] and its many subsidiaries handle worldwide logistics operations including Land Transport, Air and Ocean Freight as well as Contract Logistics/SCM, and is part of the DB Schenker organization. Since 2016, rail freight business no longer operates under the brand ''DB Schenker Rail.'' Instead, it operates as a standalone business unit under the brand name ''DB Cargo'' in Deutsche Bahn Group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.deutschebahn.com/en/db-group/business-units/db-cargo/|title=DB Cargo|website=Deutsche Bahn IR|language=en|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>.  \n\n== Key Customers ==\nDB Schenker serves many global and local firms across all industries. Notably, DB Schenker manages large and complex supply chains for multinationals such as [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lloydsloadinglist.com/freight-directory/news/DB-Schenker-to-manage-new-Apple-distribution-centre-in-India/68156.htm|title=DB Schenker to manage new Apple distribution centre in India - Lloyd's Loading List|website=www.lloydsloadinglist.com|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[Procter & Gamble]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/procter-gamble-is-latest-to-take-over-inland-warehouse-shifting-500-plus-schenker-staff|title=Procter & Gamble is latest to take over Inland warehouse, shifting 500-plus Schenker staff|date=2019-03-04|website=Press Enterprise|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[Dell]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbschenker.com/au-en/about/press/db-schenker-news/hoxton-park-grand-opening-510154|title=Hoxton Park Grand Opening|website=DB Schenker|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[ASML Holding|ASML]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbschenker.com/cn-en/about/press/corporate-news/opening-aslms-tss-centre-524518|title=Grand Opening of ASML's TSS Center operated by DB Schenker|website=DB Schenker|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>, [[BMW]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dbschenker.com/de-de/ueber-uns/presse-center/db-schenker-news/db-befoerdert-2016-ueber-40-000-container-zwischen-china-und-deutschland-13834|title=DB bef\u00f6rdert 2016 \u00fcber 40.000 Container zwischen China und Deutschland|website=DB Schenker|language=de-DE|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref> and many more.\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn 2016, DB Schenker was convicted for consecutive cases of corruption in St. Petersburg, Russia, bribing local customs officials from 2010 to mid-2012. At the time, DB Schenker involved a Russian agency for enabling the rapid flow of shipments to carmaker Ford\u2019s St. Petersburg facility. DB Schenker had to pay a penalty of \u20ac2m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cargoforwarder.eu/2016/11/06/db-schenker-convicted-of-bribery/|title=DB Schenker Convicted of Bribery|date=2016-11-06|website=CargoForwarder Global|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>.\n\nIn September 2015, then and current CEO Jochen Thewes slapped and pushed a cab driver, who refused to pick up a drunken Thewes, in downtown Singapore. He also kicked the car and caused damage. Thewes was eventually sentenced to a fine of S$1000 and two weeks of jailtime in Singapore<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ceo-gets-jail-for-slapping-cabby|title=CEO gets jail for slapping cabby|date=2016-09-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2020, DB Schenker was accused of unfair price dumping during the [[Coronavirus recession]] and related market turbulences. Using its status as a state-owned company (as subsidiary of [[Deutsche Bahn]]), it offered prices below its own production costs for some European land routes via the freight exchange [[Timocom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurotransport.de/artikel/frachten-weiter-unter-druck-db-schenker-lockt-mit-billigpreisen-11156752.html|title=Frachten weiter unter Druck: DB Schenker lockt mit Billigpreisen|last=Rathmann|first=Matthias|date=2020-04-08|website=Eurotransport|language=de|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gottfried Schenker]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Deutsche Bahn}}\n\n[[Category:Logistics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Bahn]]\n", "name_user": "81.226.196.102", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DB_Schenker"}
